For clarity, consider a fictional sketch of a celibate Catholic Monk who has, since joining the church, resisted all sexual temptation, as prescribed in the Code of Canon Law (Frazee, 1972) (\u8220\'93Why Catholic Priests Practise Celibacy,\u8221\'94 2017). By his 20th year, he has suffered much frustration, not to mention has failed to pass on his genes. However, his belief in various religious memes is stronger than ever. Why? Because of this "sunk cost" encouraged by the memeplex itself\u8212\'97the amount of time that he has remained painfully celibate. Should he become uncertain of his religion, he would have to confront the idea that he has wasted his life, missing out on a fulfilling sex life. Thus, there is a heavy cognitive barrier to rejecting the doctrine, even if doing so would make his remaining life more enjoyable.}
