Consider the example of suicide bombers. Intuitively, we might expect the families of suicide bombers to become disillusioned from their religion at the death of a son, for example, in the name of a fiction. Purely adaptively speaking, the loss of a progeny to suicide is harmful to the spread of one's genetics. However, this does not seem to be the case. Bombers are surrounded by a religious culture that idolizes the act, and families of bombers are even encouraged to celebrate (Hutchinson, 2007, p. 177) (Hafez, 2006). For example, the Palestinian Murad Tawalbeh, who attempted suicide with his brother, framed the attitudes of his sibling as such to CBS: "Because he loves me he wants me to become a martyr\u8230\'85the most exalted thing in our religion" (Simon, 2001). We could speculate that to reject the religion in the face of the suicidal wishes of a brother\u8212\'97while it would decrease the chance of further death\u8212\'97would be to admit the needlessness of the death; thus loss aversion renews one's faith and the idea of maryrdom propagates. After all, it\u8217\'92s psychologically more palatable to go on believing that one's brother is with God in Paradise than to admit they died for no good reason.}
