Sacrifice as a strengthening factor in religion is also seen in the belief, common among the Christian sect known as Jehovah's Witnesses, that blood transfusions are taboo (Singelenberg, 1990). This belief naturally leads to many run-ins between medical professionals and believers, in cases in which the believer would benefit from a treatment incorporating a transfusion (Conti et al., 2018). Particularly relevant to my argument are cases describing the reaction of religious parents to the suffering or even death of a child because of a refused treatment. A case that made headlines in 2007 concerned Mount Vernon teenager Dennis Lindberg, who died after refusing transfusions (Raftery, 2018). Notably, when asked by a reporter how Lindberg\u8217\'92s death had affected her faith, his (Jehovah's Witness) guardian Diana Mincin said it was actually strengthened (Raftery, 2018). Once again, personal, inadaptive sacrifice is actually a powerful viral meme, in that it }{\loch\cs16\rtlch\ai \ltrch\loch\i\cf17\loch
strengthens c}{\loch\cf17\loch
onviction in the wider memeplex. To question the integrity of the Bible would, for Mincin, be tantamount to admitting that Lindberg's death was totally unnecessary. The shame and trauma of such an admission thus create this powerful barrier to rejection of the harmful idea itself and the wider associated memeplex.}
