"Prosperity theology" is a Christian doctrine taught most commonly by televangelicals in America and Australia, but that has also gained popularity in Africa and South America (Novotny, 1990, p. 4) (Gbote & Kgatla, 2014). The basic teachings of the "prosperity gospel" are as follows: adherents are promised earthly riches by God, on the condition that they first pay a tribute\u8212\'97\u8220\'93seed-faith\u8221\'94\u8212\'97to their pastor (Gbote & Kgatla, 2014). It is not hard to paint such a practice as exploitative. Consider the case of Kenneth Copeland, one of America's most successful televangelists, who has previously solicited donations for several private jets which he has taken on personal holidays (Perota et al., 2015) (Shipp, 2015). Most shockingly, Copeland additionally asked followers to continue paying "seed-faith" even if they had lost jobs during COVID-19 (Gagn\u233\'e9, n.d.).}
