Thus, it is not surprising that the 20-21st centuries have seen a boom in televangelical faith, despite its dismissal as heresy by traditional Christians (Rosin, 2009). Between the 1960s and the 1980s, the number of Americans watching televangelist TV grew from 5 million to nearly 25 million (Gershon, 2015). Televangelism is only a recent example of material sacrifice; consider the encouragement of food offerings in modern Hinduism or Greek Paganism (Ferro-Luzzi, 1977) (Elderkin, 1945). Counterintuitively, as in the case of televangelism, such doctrines actually grow in the memepool, in contrast to traditional forms of the meme. Finally, there is some experimental evidence in wider social psychology to suggest a "sunk-cost" mechanism may explain the presence of such sacrifice-encouraging ideas within religion.}
